Avoid The Bullets

by: Daniel Zhao

This game was made for my level 2 project at The League of Amazing Programmers.
Click here to download and play!

1. Why I Made This Game

I decided to make this game out of curiosity in how hard a game could be without being rude about it, throwing constant obstacles left and right, though I may have done that a little. Choosing the right game was hard, as I could have done something anyone else had already done, but I decided to be creative. 2 years ago I saw a project on Scratch similar, but you couldn't die, removing the stakes, and it was ridiculously easy. Now, when I started typing code, I thought of that game. I believe I chose the most creative I could come up with, not limiting myself to the confines of games already made before, adding new enemies to mix up older ideas.

2. What I Learned

I learned that through consistent testing, the game is improved and made better overall, as well as pointing out clear issues that anyone except the developer would see. My teacher found multiple issues and exploits, while my students could not survive long enough to find any. This led to me not balancing the game, but fixing all the issues so the gameplay was more comprehensible and easier to interact with.

3. Architecture of My Game

There is multiple layers to my game. Below the menu screens, there is multiple classes in the project controlling the player, enemies, backdrops, text, as well as counters for things such as the score. If the angry suns or bullets collide with the circle at all, then the circle dies, and the game goes to the end screen. With three main screens, the menu, game, and end, more detail and complexity is built onto these blank slates.

4. Technical Implementation

I separated my classes into sections: member variables, methods, certain actions, and what each part would do. using this, I was quickly able to find any area I wanted to easily with labels. I am particularly proud of my bullets class, as I had to carefully find the correct angle and equation for each movement and rotation. through painstaking drawing, talking with mentors, and testing, I created the rotation and movement methods through extremely complex math for the age I am at.

5. Most Challenging Part

The most challenging part of this project was getting the Enemy spinners and Bullets to work completely. I believe that the only reason I was able to solve this was through my teacher, who helped me plan, code, and bring me through this hard task. Through topics like radians and trigonometry, I was able to overcome the difficulty of making them function properly.

6. Future Fixes and Updates

In the future, I would probably make it so that movement is less clunky and collision is a little better. If I were still working on this game, I would add multiple levels, the easiest being not too easy, but only having one slowly moving enemy. The hardest would have every enemy in the game, at least 5, all at maximum hardness, becoming nearly impossible. I hope anyone else who wants to can take inspiration and make something beautiful. Thanks, and best of luck on your journeys!
